To verify this conjecture, the particle size changes of D-CDs after continuous addition of Hg2+ and GSH are measured by TEM, AFM, and dynamic light scattering (DLS). Fig. 4
                        A−D show that the average diameter of D-CDs increases from 1.7 nm to 7.9 nm upon introduction of Hg2+ into D-CDs system, and subsequent addition of GSH reduces the average diameter to 1.7 nm. Interestingly, the characteristic height of D-CDs increases from 2.7 nm to 6.3 nm due to the formation of D-CDs aggregates and then recovers to 3.4 nm following depolymerization (Fig. 4E−H). Besides, sequential introduction of Hg2+ and GSH increases the average hydration diameter from 5.07 nm to 11.30 nm and then decreases to 6.24 nm, as shown in Fig. S9. These evidences indicate that D-CDs can aggregate due to addition of Hg2+, and competitive binding of GSH to Hg2+ causes the depolymerization of D-CDs@Hg2+ complexes. Moreover, we compare the FTIR spectra of D-CDs, D-CDs@Hg2+, and D-CDs@Hg2+@GSH. As shown in Fig. 4I, the characteristic bands of hydroxyl and carboxyl groups become weaker, suggesting the formation of D-CDs@Hg2+ complexes, while subsequent addition of GSH renders the characteristic bands enhance, revealing the release of D-CDs@Hg2+ complexes. Additionally, the FL lifetimes of D-CDs are monitored with successive introduction of Hg2+ and GSH, as shown in Fig. 4J. The results show that the FL lifetime of D-CDs is 3.56 ns, which reduces to 1.99 ns by Hg2+ and increases to 3.63 ns by GSH, indicating that the electron transfer occurs between D-CDs and Hg2+, but addition of GSH interrupts this process [36,37]. Based on previous reports, we infer that the aggregation of D-CDs gives rise to limited rotation of functional groups on the surface of D-CDs, which enhances π-conjugation, thereby suppressing nonradiative transitions and enhancing radiative transitions. Thus, green emission intensity of D-CDs at 550 nm gradually enhances with the increase of Hg2+ concentration. Meanwhile, the formation of D-CDs aggregates triggers electron transfer, causing the quenching of the orange FL at 616 nm. Subsequently, when GSH is introduced into the D-CDs@Hg2+ system, it competitively captures Hg2+, which leads to the depolymerization of D-CDs aggregates and the disruption of electron transfer process, resulting in the recovery of D-CDs FL (Fig. 5
                        ).
